The economic analysis was conducted to check the economic feasibility of solar still with CQDs nanofluids. The relative calculation formula was expressed in Table 4
                        , based on [58]. To make the results comparable, some parameters are assumed as follows:

                              •

n is the lifetime of the whole system setting at 10 years;


                              •

i represents the annual interest equaling to 15 %;


                              •

F is the total fixed cost;


                              •

S is the salvage value (20 % × F)

A mild manufacturing route of CQDs nanofluids was designed by microwave method coupling a simple dilution in this study, which was expected to achieve the in-situ preparation of nanofluids. Moreover, this work investigated the application potential of CQDs nanofluids in solar desalination process by a series of experiments, including stability evaluation, optical properties test, desalination performance test with a solar still and economic analysis. Some interesting results are summarized as follows:

                           1)

CQDs was prepared successfully by microwave method with the average size and concentration from 12 to 22 nm and 0.18 to 0.90 g/L, respectively, and the largest change of carbon content in the supernatant of CQDs slurry from 0.913 to 0.899 g/L within 90 days, meaning CQDs owns a good stability as the concentrated slurry and is easy to long-term store or transportation;


                           2)

Almost all saline water based CQDs nanofluids can keep stable in a wide range of salt concentration and own a good stability in thermal cycling test, but the negative effect of Ca2+ is obvious for the stability of CQDs nanofluids, so the hardness of saline water needs to be considered in the real application;


                           3)

While the precipitation formed in the NaCl concentration of 5 to 50 g/L after 90 days, interestingly, CQDs nanofluids were not failure completely, and their transmittance was still higher than that of water. An instability mechanism was proposed to explain this phenomenon, which is different from the other colloidal system with effect of salt ions due to the smaller particle size of CQDs;


                           4)

CQDs nanofluids own the effective solar absorption capacity and when the thickness of nanofluids is at 1 cm, the absorbed energy fraction is 98.93 % for 10 vol% CQDs nanofluids diluting from 30 min CQDs slurry;


                           5)

Compared with the traditional solar still, the solar still with CQDs nanofluids has a higher cumulative water yield and energy efficiency with 823 mL and 32.23 %, respectively, and the cost of water production is 0.013 to 0.015 $/L for the solar still with nanofluids by economic analysis.
